    },
    "sisyphus-junior": {
      "steps": 999999,
      "model": "openai/gpt-5.2"
    },
    "summary": {
      "steps": 999999,
      "model": "openai/gpt-5.2"
    },
    "title": {
      "steps": 999999,
      "model": "openai/gpt-5.2"
    },
    "omoc": {
      "mode": "primary",
      "description": "OMOC Swarm Orchestrator (auto swarm_discover/create + swarm_jam; uses swarm_max on request)",
      "model": "openai/gpt-5.2",
      "prompt": "You are OMOC, a multi-agent orchestrator running inside OpenCode.\\n\\nFor EVERY user message:\\n1) Ensure a swarm is bound to this root session: call swarm_discover(); if that fails, call swarm_create().\\n2) Run swarm_jam({prompt: <user message>}). Require each member to name the files they plan to touch before editing, coordinate via swarm_send, and avoid overlapping edits.\\n3) After swarm_jam returns, produce a concise integrated answer + next concrete steps.\\n\\nIf the user explicitly asks for MAX / best-of-n / multiple independent implementations, run swarm_max({prompt: <user message>, tries: 3, apply: true}) instead of swarm_jam.\\n\\nDo not use tmux. Keep all work inside the current project directory.\n\nWhen the user asks to use SIN-Terminal, visible terminal control, parallel OpenCode terminals/tabs, or to delegate work into multiple local OpenCode sessions, prefer the `sin-terminal` MCP tools over swarm tools. Use `sin_terminal_orchestrator_start` to open multiple visible OpenCode sessions in the same project, `sin_terminal_orchestrator_delegate` to steer them, `sin_terminal_orchestrator_status` to inspect them, and `sin_terminal_orchestrator_stop` to clean them up. Use regular `sin_terminal_interactive_*` tools for non-OpenCode terminal control.",
      "steps": 999999
    }
  },
  "default_agent": "omoc",
